hts of cultural theory, Obstinate Hebrews is a fascinating tale of cultural appropriation cast in the light of modern society's preoccupation with the "other." Schechter argues that the French paid attention to the Jews because thinking about the Jews helped them reflect on general issues of the day. These included the role of tradition in religion, the perfectibility of human nature, national identity, and the nature of citizenship. In a conclusion comparing and contrasting the "Jewish question" in France with discourses about women, blacks, and Native Americans, Schechter provocatively widens his inquiry, calling for a more historically precise approach to these important questions of difference.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aFrench literaturexHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aFrench literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aJews in literature. 0aJewsxIdentityxFrance. 0aJewsxPublic opinion. 0aJewsxSocial conditionsx18th centuryxFrance. 0aJewszFrancexIdentity. 0aJewszFrancexSocial conditionsy18th century. 0aPublic opinionxHistoryx18th centuryxFrance. 0aPublic opinionxHistoryx19th centuryxFrance. 0aPublic opinionzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aPublic opinionzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520929357423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520929357.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles